  "prompt": "What are the main reasons why students from Boston University don't graduate on time?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why students from Boston University, like students at many other institutions, may not graduate on time. Here are some of the primary factors:\n\n1. **Academic Challenges**: Students may struggle with the coursework, leading to repeated classes, lower GPAs, or lack of progress needed to complete their degree requirements on time.\n\n2. **Major Changes**: Switching majors can result in needing to complete different sets of prerequisites and core courses, which can extend the time needed to graduate.\n\n3. **Personal Issues**: Health problems, family emergencies, mental health concerns, or other personal issues can interfere with a student's ability to focus on their studies and stay on track.\n\n4. **Financial Constraints**: The high cost of tuition, fees, and living expenses in Boston may result in students taking a reduced course load while working part-time to cover their expenses, thus prolonging their time to graduation.\n\n5. **Institutional Factors**: Limited availability of required courses, scheduling conflicts, or issues with academic advising can impact a student\u2019s ability to enroll in the courses they need for timely graduation.\n\n6. **Internships and Study Abroad**: Participating in internships, co-op programs, or studying abroad may delay progress if these experiences cause students to take fewer courses or do not align perfectly with graduation requirements.\n\n7. **Complex Degree Requirements**: Some programs may have particularly rigorous or complex requirements that take longer to fulfill, extending the time needed to complete the degree.\n\n8. **Extracurricular Activities**: Heavy involvement in extracurricular activities, clubs, sports, or campus organizations can sometimes detract from academic focus and extend time to graduation.\n\nEfforts to address these issues typically involve increased academic support services, financial aid, better advising, and more flexible course scheduling to help students stay on track.",
